{"questionId":"3230672","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The quadratic curve, with endpoints <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, has the same gradient at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math> as the line segment.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the equation of the curve between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>equation has the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math></p>\n<p>when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo> </mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math></p>\n<p>attempt to find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> by setting <em>their</em> derivative equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math> <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> (and hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>equation has the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo> </mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></math></p>\n<p>attempt to find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math> by setting <em>their</em> derivative equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> (and hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Writing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> is incorrect and gains no marks.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"3230672","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.10b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the equation of the curve between (-2, 0) and (0, 0).","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Modelling functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.9—HL modelling functions","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.8—Use of technology to solve systems of linear equations and polynomial equations"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}